article.headline: Top-ranked Huskies trounce South Florida, remain undefeated
article.linkText: UConn earns 20-win season for 15th straight time
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Maya Moore called it perhaps the worst game Connecticut has played all season, and the top-ranked Huskies still won by 23 points.

Moore scored 23, and UConn (20-0, 7-0 Big East) beat South Florida 71-48 on Wednesday night, giving the Huskies 20 wins for the 15th consecutive season. Moore scored in double digits for the 20th consecutive game.

That's the longest such streak for a UConn player since Diana Taurasi scored in double digits in 31 consecutive games between Feb. 19, 2003 and Jan. 27, 2004.

"That's great, but it doesn't make this feeling inside feel any better, as far as the way we know we could have played and didn't," Moore said.

Renee Montgomery added 21 points for the Huskies, but was the only other UConn player in double figures. She called it a bad win.

"We were turning it over, not getting a shot at all," she said. "On defense, we weren't getting all the way out on shooters or they were getting offensive rebounds. Those are just all the things that we can control. That's when it's bad, when the things you can control, you do bad at, then that's when you have trouble."

Shantia Grace led South Florida (11-9, 1-6) with 15, just two below her average.

The Huskies held the Bulls to 30 percent shooting, but were outrebounded 39-36 and committed 18 turnovers.

"I think we battled," USF coach Jose Fernandez said. "We attacked and we stepped in and took charges. It's not about moral victories, but I saw some things today that I haven't seen in the last three weeks."

UConn was coming off wins over No. 3 North Carolina and No. 20 Notre Dame, but did not play with the same intensity.

Center Tina Charles, who had four blocked shots in the first 5:34, played just 12 minute before being benched by coach Geno Auriemma for sloppy defense. She didn't return until there was 4:30 left and the Huskies were up 61-35, finishing with eight points and four rebounds in just 13 minutes.

Auriemma said he's trying to send Charles the message that she has to be good every night if she wants to be a great player.

"That's like the messages you get from Pluto," he said. "Like when a star sends a message, do you know how long it takes to get here? Billions and billions of years, as Carl Sagan used to say. That message I sent today, when she's married and got kids she's going to call me and go, 'Coach, now I get it.'
 "

The Huskies committed 11 first-half turnovers, but led by 20 at the break. Montgomery and Moore combined for 30 of UConn's 42 first-half points. South Florida turned the ball over 13 times, and shot just 24 percent before intermission.

The Huskies hit eight of their first 11 shots, getting assists on every basket, and jumped out to a 19-11 lead. The Bulls stayed in the game by hitting four of their first eight from behind the arc. They trailed just 19-14 with 10:10 left, but managed just eight points the rest of the half.

Connecticut is the only undefeated team in Division I, and has won 33 consecutive regular season games. Over that span, the Huskies have beaten their opponents by an average of over 29 points per game.

"Every win feels like a win, but some wins are better than others," Auriemma said. "Some are great wins. Some are good wins. (There's) never a bad win."

Moore now had 340 career points in her freshman year, with as many as 19 games to play. Svetlana Abrosimove (538) and Tina Charles (456) hold the top two places on the team's freshman scoring list.

Montgomery, who was recognized before the game for becoming the 30th player in UConn history to score 1,000 points, said she expects the Huskies to have a better effort Saturday when they play host to Providence.

"I'd rather have a game like this, where we win and it feels like a loss than a loss," she said. "I'll take it, as long as we learn from it."
